snippet.textDisplay:
Umm I can't believe they forgot to include Marc Gasol or Tim Duncan for the C spot in All Decade team, yet Pau's name was brought up for 2010s, come on now. if we're going traditional position by position and we have to include a Center, Marc would be the right pick. If we were just simply filling in the best players of the decade, the list would be completely different.




Traditional:




PG: Steph(shorter body of work than some other superstars, but still won 2x mvp, a 3x champ, greatest shooter ever, ringleader of the winningest team of the 2010s. Went from all star to superstar to MVP to historically great.)
SG: James Harden (Look at how far Harden has evolved since 2012. Was drafted by OKC right before the decade. Despite being league MVP caliber in 2015-17, he has somehow even reached a more insane level from '18 till now despite increasing volume, and is the main reason Houston has even been relevant. Has been the best offensive player in the league for the last several years, I wouldn't include Kobe just bc he only had 2 great seasons left within the decade. )
SF: Kevin Durant(greatest scorer of this gen, 4x scoring champ, mvp, has been a top 2 player in the world since 2012).
PF: Lebron James(the best player of the decade). (James was an SF throughout the era, but Durant had to be included. Blake Griffin & Tim Duncan would've been the best traditional Power Forwards of the decade).
C: Marc Gasol (Anchored and spearheaded a perennial contending Grizzlies squad into countless playoff battles. Played at an extremely high level on both ends. Was destroying the Warriors inside from 2015-2018. Was the best playing Center in the West at the time when taking into account wins, impact, ability. Cousins was the most talented, AD was a young PF, and Howard was too injury prone and inconsistent.)




Honourable mention:
Tim Duncan(was still an elite big man & overall player well into the 2010s, even had one of the greatest defensive seasons in his final year).
CP3(would've easily been the best point guard of the decade if it wasn't for Steph).
Westbrook(would've been there if it wasn't for Harden. Most explosive point guard ever, 2017 MVP, made 4 West Finals with KD(!), and has routinely been a top 5 talent in the NBA in his prime before Kd left. That, and Harden's evolution along with WB's own first round losses are the only thing that hurt him.)
Blake Griffin (Was a top 3 mvp candidate in 2014, and was the league's best power forward for several years going. Powered a title contending Lob city clippers with CP3, and was unquestionably a superstar in that time. Since 2016 and due to injuries and early playoff exits, he's been less of a force and made less of an impact than before, but skillwise still one of the best bigs in the league today.
Lamarcus Aldridge: Has been the best Power Forward of the decade, offensively. No one should forget the numbers Aldridge was putting up in a Portland uniform. At one point, he was one of the most dominant players in the NBA. Unfortunately has never made a conference finals until joining Kawhi and the Spurs.




Best players period during the decade ignoring the C:




G: Steph
G: CP3 or Westbrook
G: James Harden
F: Lebron James
F: Kevin Durant

snippet.textDisplay: Technically, none of these guys know what a decade is. The 2010s decade was the 2010 season (which started in 2009) to the 2019 season (which ended in June 2019). The calendar hasn't flipped to 2020 yet, but this is the 2020 NBA season and the 2020s decade, so technically, the next decade has already started. The 2010s decade ended in June. It's just more convenient to talk about it now because the calendar is about the change.
